The paper discusses a method for transforming (dis-)similarity matrices into kernel matrices, which is a common technique in machine learning and data analysis. The paper also mentions the scalability of the method, which suggests that it may be relevant to the sub-categories of machine learning (cs.LG), data structures and algorithms (cs.DS), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), computer vision (cs.CV), and computational linguistics (cs.CL).
